The article discusses the benefits of deregulation in the United States. It argues that unnecessary regulations limit job creation and economic growth. The article states that increased regulation decreases rates of new business entry and contributes to the productivity slowdown, which leads to stagnant wages. It also highlights the negative impact of overregulation on people's ability to relocate for job opportunities and the barriers caused by state-level occupational licensing restrictions. The article mentions that the Treasury Department rules caused 75% of the federal paperwork burden in FY 2015. The administration has focused on eliminating excessive regulation and has issued 67 deregulatory actions in its first eight months, creating over $8.1 billion in cost savings. The article concludes by suggesting that continued deregulatory efforts can lead to further cost savings and economic growth.